You have it really
hot, what happens

01:00:23.642 --> 01:00:25.350
is every once in a
while an electron will

01:00:25.350 --> 01:00:27.683
get nailed by a little thermal
fluctuation in the system

01:00:27.683 --> 01:00:30.222
and get excited above the gap.

01:00:30.222 --> 01:00:32.180
And now it's in a super--
and generically, it's

01:00:32.180 --> 01:00:33.990
going to be in a superposition
state of one of these excited

01:00:33.990 --> 01:00:34.102
states.

01:00:34.102 --> 01:00:35.685
So it's in general
going to be moving.

01:00:35.685 --> 01:00:36.330
It can radiate.

01:00:36.330 --> 01:00:38.189
It will eventually
fall back down.

01:00:38.189 --> 01:00:39.730
But you're constantly
being buffeted.

01:00:39.730 --> 01:00:41.146
The sea of electrons
is constantly

01:00:41.146 --> 01:00:43.800
being buffeted by this
thermal fluctuation.

01:00:43.800 --> 01:00:45.657
And as a result,
you constantly have

01:00:45.657 --> 01:00:47.490
electrons being excited
up, cruising around,

01:00:47.490 --> 01:00:49.070
falling back down.

01:00:49.070 --> 01:00:52.380
So you end up with some
population of electrons.

01:00:52.380 --> 01:00:54.390
And they can ask--
and both when asked,

01:00:54.390 --> 01:00:55.960
although not quite
in this language,

01:00:55.960 --> 01:00:58.210
how likely are you to
get an electron up here?

01:00:58.210 --> 01:01:01.030
How likely is an electron
to be excited up thermally?

01:01:01.030 --> 01:01:03.780
And those of you taking 8.04
will know the answer to this.

01:01:03.780 --> 01:01:10.361
The probability goes as e to
the minus delta e over kt.

01:01:10.361 --> 01:01:12.860
So let's think of this where
this is the Boltzmann constant.

01:01:12.860 --> 01:01:13.818
So what does this mean?

01:01:13.818 --> 01:01:17.132
At very low temperatures, if
the gap isn't 0, then this is 0.

01:01:17.132 --> 01:01:18.116
It doesn't happen.

01:01:18.116 --> 01:01:20.490
But at large temperatures,
the denominator here is large.

01:01:20.490 --> 01:01:21.990
If the temperature
is large compared

01:01:21.990 --> 01:01:24.750
to the width of the gap,
then this is a small number.

01:01:24.750 --> 01:01:26.990
And e to the minus of a
small number is close to 1.

01:01:26.990 --> 01:01:28.750
So at high temperature,
you're very

01:01:28.750 --> 01:01:30.542
likely to excite
electrons up here.

01:01:30.542 --> 01:01:32.125
And now if you have
electrons up here,

01:01:32.125 --> 01:01:33.624
you have a bunch
of available states

01:01:33.624 --> 01:01:35.230
down here-- also
known as holes--

01:01:35.230 --> 01:01:37.021
and you have a bunch
of available electrons

01:01:37.021 --> 01:01:38.744
up here with lots
of available states.

01:01:38.744 --> 01:01:41.035
So at a high temperature, a
material with a small gap--

01:01:41.035 --> 01:01:42.743
or at least at
temperatures high compared

01:01:42.743 --> 01:01:45.570
to the size of the gap--
it's basically a conductor.

01:01:45.570 --> 01:01:48.580
And at low temperatures,
it's basically an insulator.

01:01:48.580 --> 01:01:50.220
This is called a semiconductor.

01:01:50.220 --> 01:01:58.350
And there are notes on
the Stellar web page

01:01:58.350 --> 01:02:01.560
that discuss in a little more
detail what I just went through

01:02:01.560 --> 01:02:04.230
and show you how you
build a transistor out

01:02:04.230 --> 01:02:05.570
of a semiconductor.

01:02:05.570 --> 01:02:09.340
And the important bit
of physics is just this.

01:02:09.340 --> 01:02:10.330
OK.

01:02:10.330 --> 01:02:13.520
So that finishes us
up for the band gap

01:02:13.520 --> 01:02:14.934
systems for periodic potentials.

01:02:14.934 --> 01:02:16.350
We've done something
kind of cool.

01:02:16.350 --> 01:02:19.220
We've explained why
diamonds are transparent.

01:02:19.220 --> 01:02:21.470
We've explained why
they don't conduct.

01:02:21.470 --> 01:02:24.130
We've explained why copper
does and it's opaque.

01:02:24.130 --> 01:02:26.942
And that's pretty good
for 15 minutes of work.

01:02:26.942 --> 01:02:28.710
It's not bad.

01:02:28.710 --> 01:02:31.055
But along the way, we also
talked about the analogous

01:02:31.055 --> 01:02:34.390
system of what are
called photonic crystals.

01:02:34.390 --> 01:02:37.640
Systems of periodic
arrays of dielectrics.

01:02:37.640 --> 01:02:38.624
Like wave guides.

01:02:38.624 --> 01:02:40.040
And those have the
same structure.

01:02:40.040 --> 01:02:42.860
They have bands of
allowed energy and gaps

01:02:42.860 --> 01:02:46.107
of disallowed energies where
no waves propagate through.

01:02:46.107 --> 01:02:47.690
So you might think
that's a little bit

01:02:47.690 --> 01:02:48.750
of a ridiculous example.

01:02:48.750 --> 01:02:50.700
So just to close
this off, you've

01:02:50.700 --> 01:02:53.110
all seen a good example of
a photonic crystal flying

01:02:53.110 --> 01:02:55.990
past you.

01:02:55.990 --> 01:03:01.580
You know that highly reflective
at very specific frequency

01:03:01.580 --> 01:03:03.780
structure on the
surface of a butterfly

01:03:03.780 --> 01:03:05.370
wing that makes
it shiny and blue?

01:03:05.370 --> 01:03:06.200
It looks metallic.

01:03:06.200 --> 01:03:08.620
It looks like it's
a crystal reflecting

01:03:08.620 --> 01:03:09.620
in a specific frequency.

01:03:09.620 --> 01:03:10.890
At some sharp blue.

01:03:10.890 --> 01:03:12.850
And the reason is, it's
a photonic crystal.

01:03:12.850 --> 01:03:14.129
It is exactly this form.

01:03:14.129 --> 01:03:15.670
If you look at it
under a microscope,

01:03:15.670 --> 01:03:18.300
you see little rays
of protein which

01:03:18.300 --> 01:03:20.720
have different
dielectric than air.

01:03:20.720 --> 01:03:24.270
And they form exact crystals--
or not exact, but very good

01:03:24.270 --> 01:03:27.780
crystals-- that reflect at
very specific wavelengths.

01:03:27.780 --> 01:03:30.980
And as a consequence, they
have a metallic sheen.

01:03:30.980 --> 01:03:34.560
So why would a butterfly
put a photonic crystal

01:03:34.560 --> 01:03:35.690
on its surface?

01:03:35.690 --> 01:03:36.940
Well it's extremely light.

01:03:36.940 --> 01:03:37.827
It's fairly rigid.

01:03:37.827 --> 01:03:39.660
It looks shiny and
metallic without actually

01:03:39.660 --> 01:03:41.080
being shiny and metallic.

01:03:41.080 --> 01:03:44.260
And it's not a pigment, so it
doesn't absorb light and decay

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:44.966
over time.

01:03:44.966 --> 01:03:46.590
It's like the best
thing you could ever

01:03:46.590 --> 01:03:48.881
do if you wanted to be a
shiny, fluttery, flying thing.

01:03:52.241 --> 01:03:52.740
Anyway.

01:03:52.740 --> 01:03:54.960
So there's an incredible
amount of physics

01:03:54.960 --> 01:03:56.920
in this story of the band gaps.

01:03:56.920 --> 01:04:00.180
And consider this an
introduction to the topic.

01:04:00.180 --> 01:04:00.940
OK.

01:04:00.940 --> 01:04:02.730
So that's it for band gaps.

01:04:02.730 --> 01:04:04.845
And I want to move
on to the remainder,

01:04:04.845 --> 01:04:06.380
the last topic of our course.

01:04:06.380 --> 01:04:08.255
Which is going to be
entanglement and quantum

01:04:08.255 --> 01:04:08.870
computation.

01:04:08.870 --> 01:04:12.010
And here I need to give
you one quick observation

01:04:12.010 --> 01:04:14.584
and then move on to
the punchline of today.

01:04:14.584 --> 01:04:16.000
The one quick
observation is this.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:17.992
We've talked about
identical particles before.

01:04:17.992 --> 01:04:20.450
And we've talked about identical
particles in funny states.

01:04:20.450 --> 01:04:23.500
So for example, imagine I
have two particles described

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:25.570
by a wave function where
the first particle could

01:04:25.570 --> 01:04:30.500
be in the state a and the
second particles in the state b.

01:04:30.500 --> 01:04:33.189
And I can build a wave function
for the first particle being

01:04:33.189 --> 01:04:34.980
in state a and the
second particle in state

01:04:34.980 --> 01:04:35.980
b in the following way.

01:04:35.980 --> 01:04:38.780
So let's say position
a and position b.

01:04:38.780 --> 01:04:42.730
I could take a single particle
wave function, chi of a,

01:04:42.730 --> 01:04:45.851
and a single particle
wave functions phi of b.

01:04:45.851 --> 01:04:47.600
And we've talked about
what this tells us.

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:49.370
And you've studied this
on your problem set.

01:04:49.370 --> 01:04:51.620
What this tells you is that
the probability of finding

01:04:51.620 --> 01:04:53.717
the particle at point A
is given by chi a squared.

01:04:53.717 --> 01:04:56.050
And this is normalized, so
when we integrate against it,

01:04:56.050 --> 01:04:57.517
we get 1.

01:04:57.517 --> 01:04:59.100
And similarly, the
probability that we

01:04:59.100 --> 01:05:02.190
find the second particle at
b is this thing norm squared.

01:05:02.190 --> 01:05:05.296
And it's independent
of what a is.

01:05:05.296 --> 01:05:06.670
But we also
studied-- and so this

01:05:06.670 --> 01:05:07.961
was called the distinguishable.

01:05:07.961 --> 01:05:12.400
We also studied the symmetric
configuration, which

01:05:12.400 --> 01:05:16.790
was equal to 1 over
root phi, root 2.

01:05:16.790 --> 01:05:18.016
Chi of a.

01:05:18.016 --> 01:05:21.650
Phi of b.

01:05:21.650 --> 01:05:26.890
Symmetric, plus
chi of b phi of a.

01:05:26.890 --> 01:05:29.140
And this tells us
something totally awesome.

01:05:29.140 --> 01:05:36.990
What's the probability that I
find the first particle at a?

01:05:36.990 --> 01:05:41.070
It's the norm squared of
chi of a phi of b, right?

01:05:41.070 --> 01:05:42.730
If we integrate
over all phi b, this

01:05:42.730 --> 01:05:44.460
is the norm squared
integrates to 1.

01:05:44.460 --> 01:05:45.277
So it's fine.

01:05:45.277 --> 01:05:46.610
So there's a factor of one half.

01:05:46.610 --> 01:05:50.400
We either find it at
chi of a or chi of b.

01:05:50.400 --> 01:05:54.810
However if I tell you that I've
measured the first particle

01:05:54.810 --> 01:05:56.697
and I find it in
the state chi, what

01:05:56.697 --> 01:05:58.280
can you say about
the second particle?

01:06:01.010 --> 01:06:02.890
It's in the state phi.

01:06:02.890 --> 01:06:05.490
If you know the first
particle's in the state chi,

01:06:05.490 --> 01:06:06.990
the second part is
in the state phi.

01:06:06.990 --> 01:06:09.490
Because we measured it and
it's not in the state--

01:06:09.490 --> 01:06:12.340
the first particle's
not in the state phi.

01:06:12.340 --> 01:06:13.870
So measuring one
particle tells you

01:06:13.870 --> 01:06:15.536
something about the
second particle.

01:06:15.536 --> 01:06:16.910
And this is deeply
disconcerting,

01:06:16.910 --> 01:06:18.618
because I could've
taken these particles,

01:06:18.618 --> 01:06:20.040
put them in this
entangled state,

01:06:20.040 --> 01:06:23.120
and sent one particle
off to a distant planet

01:06:23.120 --> 01:06:26.250
and the second particle
to my sister in DC.

01:06:26.250 --> 01:06:28.830
And my sister measures
this second particle

01:06:28.830 --> 01:06:31.110
and determines what state
it's in and is immediately

01:06:31.110 --> 01:06:34.940
determined what state
the first particle is

01:06:34.940 --> 01:06:37.990
in over in this distant
planet Zorg, right?

01:06:37.990 --> 01:06:39.817
So that's deeply disconcerting.

01:06:39.817 --> 01:06:42.150
And to those of us who have
studied quantum mechanics up

01:06:42.150 --> 01:06:43.858
to this point-- which
we all in this room

01:06:43.858 --> 01:06:45.950
have-- to those of us
who have studied quantum

01:06:45.950 --> 01:06:47.562
mechanics to this
level of development

01:06:47.562 --> 01:06:49.520
and understand that it
is a correct description

01:06:49.520 --> 01:06:52.870
of many experiments, this
should be yet another moment

01:06:52.870 --> 01:06:54.112
of serious discomfort.

01:06:54.112 --> 01:06:56.195
We've run into a bunch of
these over the semester.

01:06:56.195 --> 01:06:57.861
But this one should
be troubling to you.

01:06:57.861 --> 01:06:59.210
Because look.

01:06:59.210 --> 01:07:01.370
How can something
here dramatically

01:07:01.370 --> 01:07:03.460
change the state,
the configuration,

01:07:03.460 --> 01:07:06.222
the initial configuration, of a
particle arbitrarily far away?

01:07:06.222 --> 01:07:07.430
Isn't that deeply concerning?

01:07:07.430 --> 01:07:08.700
And if you think
about relativity,

01:07:08.700 --> 01:07:10.750
this should be all the
more deeply disconcerting.

01:07:10.750 --> 01:07:13.280
Because how does relativistic
causality fit into this?

01:07:13.280 --> 01:07:15.270
So there was a person
that roughly this time,

01:07:15.270 --> 01:07:17.840
a little earlier, who was
troubled by this problem.

01:07:17.840 --> 01:07:19.240
And his name was Einstein.

01:07:19.240 --> 01:07:21.350
And so one of the things
that's kind of amazing

01:07:21.350 --> 01:07:25.340
is that he created a thought
experiment which we're

01:07:25.340 --> 01:07:28.440
going to study in detail next
week called the EPR experiment.

01:07:28.440 --> 01:07:30.380
And there's a beautiful
historical story

01:07:30.380 --> 01:07:32.510
about the setting
and the meaning

01:07:32.510 --> 01:07:34.000
and the particular person.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:35.583
And unfortunately,
I'm not a historian

01:07:35.583 --> 01:07:37.866
so I can't tell you that story.

01:07:37.866 --> 01:07:39.490
It sure would be nice
if we had someone

01:07:39.490 --> 01:07:41.360
who wrote a
biography of Einstein

01:07:41.360 --> 01:07:43.800
to tell you a little
bit about that story.

01:07:43.800 --> 01:07:45.300
Oh look, it's Tom
Levenson who wrote

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:46.520
a biography about Einstein.

