01:11:53.650 --> 01:11:55.660
Who had two quirks.

01:11:55.660 --> 01:12:01.810
An unusual color sense and a
taste for mismatched socks.

01:12:01.810 --> 01:12:05.060
And so Bell used to say, if you
saw Bartelstein and you could

01:12:05.060 --> 01:12:08.740
only see one leg and
that sock was pink,

01:12:08.740 --> 01:12:15.580
you knew to a certainty that
the other sock was not pink.

01:12:15.580 --> 01:12:19.490
He comes up I think--
I'm trying to remember

01:12:19.490 --> 01:12:21.690
who this is originally
attributed to.

01:12:21.690 --> 01:12:22.190
Same thing.

01:12:22.190 --> 01:12:30.320
If you have a coin and you
cut it in half down the-- so

01:12:30.320 --> 01:12:32.110
you've got two coin shape disks.

01:12:32.110 --> 01:12:33.979
You cut the disk in
half, not-- and you

01:12:33.979 --> 01:12:36.270
have one side that's the head
and the other side that's

01:12:36.270 --> 01:12:38.120
the tail.

01:12:38.120 --> 01:12:40.120
And they're separated.

01:12:40.120 --> 01:12:41.966
They get handed to two
different gamblers.

01:12:41.966 --> 01:12:44.340
And one gambler tries to cheat
the gambling establishment

01:12:44.340 --> 01:12:46.404
by tossing in his half coin.

01:12:46.404 --> 01:12:47.820
And you see the
head that you know

01:12:47.820 --> 01:12:50.890
somebody-- somebody
at some other casino

01:12:50.890 --> 01:12:53.660
is cheating by tossing
in the half coin that

01:12:53.660 --> 01:12:54.820
only has a tail on it.

01:12:54.820 --> 01:12:56.653
So there are lots of
ways to represent this.

01:12:56.653 --> 01:12:59.795
And many physicists
being very witty indeed

01:12:59.795 --> 01:13:03.640
have come up with
different metaphors for it.

01:13:06.240 --> 01:13:13.930
So Allan just described for
you the basic claim in EPR.

01:13:13.930 --> 01:13:14.650
Its weirdness.

01:13:14.650 --> 01:13:16.930
That you have two
particles that are

01:13:16.930 --> 01:13:19.560
entangled in some way and
then go their separate ways.

01:13:19.560 --> 01:13:25.650
And thus you have--
if you have knowledge

01:13:25.650 --> 01:13:28.410
of what's the state of one,
you have certain knowledge

01:13:28.410 --> 01:13:32.420
of the state of the
other, violating

01:13:32.420 --> 01:13:34.610
relativistic ideas of locality.

01:13:34.610 --> 01:13:37.950
And just kind of
making you queasy

01:13:37.950 --> 01:13:41.050
if you're sort of
approaching it naively.

01:13:41.050 --> 01:13:42.860
What Einstein,
Podolsky, and Rosen

01:13:42.860 --> 01:13:47.490
argued was actually something
a little bit-- in fact,

01:13:47.490 --> 01:13:51.110
the paper comes to an end
on that note of queasiness.

01:13:51.110 --> 01:13:53.440
But what they argue is a
little bit more subtle.

01:13:53.440 --> 01:13:55.205
Because what they said is, OK.

01:13:57.546 --> 01:13:59.045
You perform this
thought experiment.

01:13:59.045 --> 01:14:00.990
You send the two particles off.

01:14:00.990 --> 01:14:03.600
You measure position of one,
you know absolutely the position

01:14:03.600 --> 01:14:05.370
of the other.

01:14:05.370 --> 01:14:08.220
You've conferred--
and the paper turns

01:14:08.220 --> 01:14:11.960
on a discussion
of the connection

01:14:11.960 --> 01:14:15.120
between a measurement--
a physical measurement--

01:14:15.120 --> 01:14:17.630
and a property of
physical reality.

01:14:17.630 --> 01:14:20.050
And they have definition
for what reality is.

01:14:20.050 --> 01:14:25.040
And that is something whose-- if
you can perform a measurement,

01:14:25.040 --> 01:14:26.985
you know that
quantity absolutely.

01:14:30.680 --> 01:14:33.480
I don't have the mathematics
to express that properly.

01:14:33.480 --> 01:14:36.780
But that'll do for
this hand waving.

01:14:36.780 --> 01:14:38.320
You can then do
another experiment

01:14:38.320 --> 01:14:40.660
and measure a
complementary property.

01:14:40.660 --> 01:14:42.462
And you know that
piece of reality.

01:14:42.462 --> 01:14:46.520
But you can't do the--
so on the one hand,

01:14:46.520 --> 01:14:52.410
quantum mechanics says you
can't know physical reality

01:14:52.410 --> 01:14:54.300
to this level of precision.

01:14:54.300 --> 01:15:00.590
And on the other hand,
the fact that you

01:15:00.590 --> 01:15:07.640
can do that measurement violates
the relativistic picture

01:15:07.640 --> 01:15:08.880
of reality.

01:15:08.880 --> 01:15:13.090
So you have what they
claimed was a paradox.

01:15:13.090 --> 01:15:15.860
And this paper was published.

01:15:15.860 --> 01:15:22.010
And it received a range of
reactions from indifference

01:15:22.010 --> 01:15:25.034
by younger physicists who said,
we don't care that it's weird.

01:15:25.034 --> 01:15:26.950
We're going to keep on
doing quantum mechanics

01:15:26.950 --> 01:15:29.150
and performing experiments
and making measurements.

01:15:29.150 --> 01:15:30.160
And just see where
this leads us.

01:15:30.160 --> 01:15:31.993
Remember, this is
happening in the mid '30s.

01:15:31.993 --> 01:15:35.760
1935.

01:15:35.760 --> 01:15:39.730
One of these three books will
tell me precisely in a moment.

01:15:39.730 --> 01:15:45.930
And the quantum theory, as it
turned into quantum mechanics,

01:15:45.930 --> 01:15:49.250
developed in its first
period between '23 and '27.

01:15:49.250 --> 01:15:53.120
And by '35, you have enormous
numbers of productive results

01:15:53.120 --> 01:15:55.260
and unexpected things
and the prediction

01:15:55.260 --> 01:15:58.770
of the positron and
then its observation.

01:15:58.770 --> 01:16:02.990
And I mean, the theory is
enormously, dramatically,

01:16:02.990 --> 01:16:05.030
excitingly productive.

01:16:05.030 --> 01:16:08.780
So those who are really
heads down doing the work

01:16:08.780 --> 01:16:13.810
are, for the most part,
saying, this is fine.

01:16:13.810 --> 01:16:16.390
We'll get back to it when we're
old and retired and bored.

01:16:18.920 --> 01:16:20.360
But that wasn't
the uniform case.

01:16:20.360 --> 01:16:24.180
And most notably
Niels Bohr found

01:16:24.180 --> 01:16:26.780
this paper really troubling.

01:16:26.780 --> 01:16:29.600
And spent about six
weeks, apparently,

01:16:29.600 --> 01:16:32.310
discussing this and trying to
come up with a response to it.

01:16:32.310 --> 01:16:34.010
And what he responded
was essentially

01:16:34.010 --> 01:16:40.540
that-- in some ways, it
was the same reaction

01:16:40.540 --> 01:16:42.280
as his younger colleagues.

01:16:42.280 --> 01:16:44.420
Get over it.

01:16:44.420 --> 01:16:47.530
But more precisely,
it was he said,

01:16:47.530 --> 01:16:49.050
there's no
description of reality

01:16:49.050 --> 01:16:51.530
that excludes the measuring
apparatus anymore.

01:16:51.530 --> 01:16:56.521
You can't make statements
about physical reality

01:16:56.521 --> 01:16:59.020
unless you include a description
of the measuring apparatus.

01:16:59.020 --> 01:17:01.304
And you've said that we can
measure this one quantity

01:17:01.304 --> 01:17:02.970
with precision and
know the other thing.

01:17:02.970 --> 01:17:05.303
And then we can subsequently,
in a separate observation,

01:17:05.303 --> 01:17:08.810
measure a complimentary
quality and know the other one.

01:17:08.810 --> 01:17:12.650
You still can't know much
them at the same time.

01:17:12.650 --> 01:17:16.980
It's still true that the
complementarity in essence

01:17:16.980 --> 01:17:20.730
means that once you know
one part of the picture,

01:17:20.730 --> 01:17:23.550
you know some other
part the picture.

01:17:23.550 --> 01:17:27.570
And that's just the nature
of the quantum world.

01:17:27.570 --> 01:17:30.940
Einstein had argued that
the EPR paradox suggested

01:17:30.940 --> 01:17:33.140
that quantum mechanics
was incomplete.

01:17:33.140 --> 01:17:35.740
And Bohr essentially
responded in effect

01:17:35.740 --> 01:17:38.935
that Einstein's description of
quantum mechanical explanation

01:17:38.935 --> 01:17:39.560
was inadequate.

01:17:43.686 --> 01:17:45.060
The important
thing to remember--

01:17:45.060 --> 01:17:49.480
and I want to just spend a
couple minutes going back

01:17:49.480 --> 01:17:51.890
into the pre-history
of all this,

01:17:51.890 --> 01:17:53.530
and then a couple
minutes speculating

01:17:53.530 --> 01:17:56.760
on why Einstein reached
the position he did.

01:17:56.760 --> 01:17:59.950
And what that might tell you
about the practice of science

01:17:59.950 --> 01:18:04.470
as a lived experience
as opposed to one

01:18:04.470 --> 01:18:07.730
reflected in your textbooks.

01:18:07.730 --> 01:18:10.420
But the thing to remember
is that there's nothing

01:18:10.420 --> 01:18:13.600
logically wrong
with the EPR paper.

01:18:13.600 --> 01:18:14.100
Right?

01:18:14.100 --> 01:18:14.600
You know.

01:18:17.420 --> 01:18:21.370
It does what it says it does and
there's no overt error in it.

01:18:21.370 --> 01:18:24.610
And there's nothing wrong
with Bohr's response.

01:18:24.610 --> 01:18:26.540
And in fact, when the
experiments were--

01:18:26.540 --> 01:18:32.910
Bell formalized the-- what
Bell's inequality really does

01:18:32.910 --> 01:18:34.840
is it formalized
the two arguments.

01:18:34.840 --> 01:18:37.300
It says, if Bohr
is right, you will

01:18:37.300 --> 01:18:38.720
observe this in the experiment.

01:18:38.720 --> 01:18:40.730
And if Einstein is
right, you would

01:18:40.730 --> 01:18:41.970
observe something different.

01:18:41.970 --> 01:18:44.210
The experiments were
done, and I imagine

01:18:44.210 --> 01:18:46.530
are still being done, as
sort of demonstrations.

01:18:46.530 --> 01:18:48.780
And they showed that Bohr's
interpretation was correct

01:18:48.780 --> 01:18:52.490
and that yes, quantum
mechanics produces results

01:18:52.490 --> 01:18:56.150
that are non-local just
as Allan described to you.

01:18:56.150 --> 01:18:58.980
And that the world really
is as strange as people

01:18:58.980 --> 01:19:01.990
first glimpsed in
1925, '26, and '27.

01:19:01.990 --> 01:19:07.660
And the question of whether
or not that strangeness

01:19:07.660 --> 01:19:10.244
is adequately explained
without the explanations

01:19:10.244 --> 01:19:11.910
that you're going to
learn in this class

01:19:11.910 --> 01:19:14.285
and subsequent ones are
quote "complete" or not.

01:19:14.285 --> 01:19:18.490
And completeness is a very
funny, very, very tricky

01:19:18.490 --> 01:19:19.220
concept.

01:19:19.220 --> 01:19:23.880
But the question whether or
not the framework of quantum

01:19:23.880 --> 01:19:28.830
mechanics is somehow
unsatisfactory in any kind

01:19:28.830 --> 01:19:31.470
of formal a technical
sense is one

01:19:31.470 --> 01:19:34.891
that's at least partly dependent
on your scientific temperament,

01:19:34.891 --> 01:19:35.390
I think.

01:19:38.570 --> 01:19:43.020
So that's the cartoon version
of what happened in '35.

01:19:43.020 --> 01:19:44.710
Einstein with his
two young colleagues

01:19:44.710 --> 01:19:49.140
proposes-- really you
should understand the EPR

01:19:49.140 --> 01:19:52.770
paper as a description in detail
of a consequence of quantum

01:19:52.770 --> 01:19:55.934
theory as it was then
expressed with the conclusion--

01:19:55.934 --> 01:19:57.600
and I just want to
read you this thing--

01:19:57.600 --> 01:20:00.270
no reasonable
definition of reality

01:20:00.270 --> 01:20:03.020
could be expected to
permit such a result.

01:20:06.100 --> 01:20:10.220
In fact, it's called a
paradox, but it isn't.

01:20:10.220 --> 01:20:11.840
It's a complaint.

01:20:11.840 --> 01:20:15.250
You know, it's a memo to
the Flying Spaghetti Monster

01:20:15.250 --> 01:20:17.584
that the universe
shouldn't be this way

01:20:17.584 --> 01:20:19.750
if, in fact, experiments
turn out to show that it is

01:20:19.750 --> 01:20:20.430
and they have.

01:20:25.850 --> 01:20:28.420
The oddity here for a
biographer of Einstein

01:20:28.420 --> 01:20:30.430
opposed to a physicist
is given what

01:20:30.430 --> 01:20:34.400
you know about Einstein between
1879 when he's born and say,

01:20:34.400 --> 01:20:37.060
1925 or so when he
completes the last

01:20:37.060 --> 01:20:38.226
of his really great physics.

01:20:41.100 --> 01:20:46.059
How could-- I mean,
I actually keep--

01:20:46.059 --> 01:20:48.600
I've been working on Einstein
off and on for years and years.

01:20:48.600 --> 01:20:54.880
I keep finding out new ways in
which he's just inconceivably

01:20:54.880 --> 01:20:58.030
bright and on target and with
a nose for the right problem

01:20:58.030 --> 01:20:59.490
and insightful.

01:20:59.490 --> 01:21:02.820
And yet by the 1935,
10 years later,

01:21:02.820 --> 01:21:05.070
he's still a
relatively young man.

01:21:05.070 --> 01:21:06.920
He's in his '50s.

01:21:06.920 --> 01:21:11.390
Which being in my '50s I think
is an extremely young man.

01:21:11.390 --> 01:21:14.110
Just 10 years after
doing work that's

01:21:14.110 --> 01:21:19.160
right on the edge of
modern quantum mechanics

01:21:19.160 --> 01:21:21.230
that is essential
to its foundation.

01:21:21.230 --> 01:21:23.290
That's really extraordinary.

01:21:23.290 --> 01:21:24.950
10 years after
that, he's saying,

01:21:24.950 --> 01:21:26.820
no reasonable
definition of reality

01:21:26.820 --> 01:21:31.020
should be permitted
to behave this way.

01:21:31.020 --> 01:21:32.621
Where does that come from?

01:21:32.621 --> 01:21:34.620
Well the first thing I
want to tell you-- again,

01:21:34.620 --> 01:21:37.410
this is all going to be
a really cartoon version.

01:21:37.410 --> 01:21:40.040
Because there's not
much time, I understand.

01:21:40.040 --> 01:21:44.720
Is that Einstein-- I
mean, how much are you

01:21:44.720 --> 01:21:48.590
aware of Einstein's role in the
creation of the quantum theory?

01:21:48.590 --> 01:21:49.090
A lot.

01:21:49.090 --> 01:21:49.831
I mean, a lot?

01:21:49.831 --> 01:21:50.330
None?

01:21:50.330 --> 01:21:50.829
OK.

01:21:53.590 --> 01:21:55.240
I mean, I'm going
to make a claim

01:21:55.240 --> 01:21:59.790
that except for Heisenberg,
Schrodinger, maybe Bohr.

01:21:59.790 --> 01:22:00.700
Maybe Born.

01:22:00.700 --> 01:22:02.197
Maybe a couple of others.

01:22:02.197 --> 01:22:04.030
There's no one more
important to the quantum

01:22:04.030 --> 01:22:05.720
theory than Einstein.

01:22:05.720 --> 01:22:07.250
And you could maybe
even argue that

01:22:07.250 --> 01:22:10.480
from a sort of
foundational point of view

01:22:10.480 --> 01:22:13.780
that without Einstein,
rigorous thinking about quantum

01:22:13.780 --> 01:22:16.210
mechanics would have
taken much, much longer.

01:22:16.210 --> 01:22:19.540
I mean, he's really
central to it.

01:22:19.540 --> 01:22:24.200
Planck in 1900 publishes
as an ad hoc solution

01:22:24.200 --> 01:22:29.080
to the black body problem
the first quantum theory.

01:22:29.080 --> 01:22:33.350
In 1905, Einstein says
it's not an ad hoc thing.

01:22:33.350 --> 01:22:37.730
If you look at the
photoelectric effect

01:22:37.730 --> 01:22:41.660
is the particular problem he's
dealing with in explanation.

01:22:41.660 --> 01:22:44.340
But that's really-- the behavior
of the photoelectric effect

01:22:44.340 --> 01:22:47.360
is really presented as the
confirmation of this idea

01:22:47.360 --> 01:22:51.520
that light exists as quanta with
particular kinds of behavior.

01:22:51.520 --> 01:22:54.920
And from 1905 on, he
spends probably more time

01:22:54.920 --> 01:22:58.260
on quantum problems than he did
on any other physics problems.

01:22:58.260 --> 01:23:00.060
Certainly more
than on relativity.

01:23:00.060 --> 01:23:01.590
Though he spent
enormous energy on

01:23:01.590 --> 01:23:03.406
special and general relativity.

01:23:03.406 --> 01:23:05.530
One of most amazing things
about Einstein, in fact,

01:23:05.530 --> 01:23:10.260
is that despite the fact
that he's seen and appears

01:23:10.260 --> 01:23:13.420
by 1935 to be this hidebound
old guy who can't accommodate

01:23:13.420 --> 01:23:17.064
himself to the new world is he
had an extraordinary capacity

01:23:17.064 --> 01:23:19.230
to do what the Red Queen
did in Alice in Wonderland.

01:23:19.230 --> 01:23:21.800
and believe two impossible
things before breakfast.

01:23:21.800 --> 01:23:23.220
Just think in 1905.

01:23:23.220 --> 01:23:27.290
April, he publishes The
Quantum Theory Of Light.

01:23:27.290 --> 01:23:29.850
June he publishes
Special Relativity,

01:23:29.850 --> 01:23:32.470
which treats light as a wave.

01:23:32.470 --> 01:23:36.310
And makes no mention of
his revolutionary-- I mean,

01:23:36.310 --> 01:23:38.740
he called it revolutionary
in a private letter in 1905.

01:23:38.740 --> 01:23:42.180
So he knew what he had in
the quantum theory of light.

01:23:42.180 --> 01:23:45.301
But in special relativity, go
read the special relativity

01:23:45.301 --> 01:23:45.800
paper.

01:23:45.800 --> 01:23:48.210
It's actually lovely reading.

01:23:48.210 --> 01:23:51.910
And you'll see he doesn't
even nod in that direction.

01:23:51.910 --> 01:23:55.150
He doesn't say, you know this
is a hero-- he says nothing.

01:23:55.150 --> 01:23:56.736
So he's capable of
doing excellent--

01:23:56.736 --> 01:23:58.110
and there's a
reason that year is

01:23:58.110 --> 01:24:00.760
called the annus mirabilis,
the year of miracles.

01:24:00.760 --> 01:24:02.190
And in part it's
because Einstein

01:24:02.190 --> 01:24:05.790
is able to actually really
focus on these things.

01:24:05.790 --> 01:24:08.320
And I realize class
is almost over.

01:24:08.320 --> 01:24:12.950
So there's several more steps
in Einstein's quantum journey.

01:24:12.950 --> 01:24:19.170
But you know, what
you should take away

01:24:19.170 --> 01:24:23.260
is that Einstein's
ability to deal

01:24:23.260 --> 01:24:25.837
with the problems
of quantum pictures

01:24:25.837 --> 01:24:27.670
extends to the point--
he's the first person

01:24:27.670 --> 01:24:29.600
to suggest there might be
a problem with causality

01:24:29.600 --> 01:24:30.474
in quantum mechanics.

01:24:30.474 --> 01:24:32.540
He does this in
1917, eight years

01:24:32.540 --> 01:24:34.600
before quantum
mechanics is invented.

01:24:34.600 --> 01:24:37.770
When he starts looking at what
the quote "classical" quantum

01:24:37.770 --> 01:24:40.100
theory tells you
about the emission

01:24:40.100 --> 01:24:41.860
of radiation from
an excited atom.

01:24:41.860 --> 01:24:43.990
He realized you can't
predict it precisely.

01:24:43.990 --> 01:24:45.930
Radioactive decay
has the same problem.

01:24:45.930 --> 01:24:47.530
He says, well-- he
writes in a letter.

01:24:47.530 --> 01:24:50.170
I don't want to give up
causality, but we may have to.

01:24:50.170 --> 01:24:52.440
So he's aware of these things.

01:24:52.440 --> 01:24:55.380
So I see class is
over now at 12:30.

01:24:55.380 --> 01:24:56.150
OK, sorry.

01:24:56.150 --> 01:24:58.820
So juts to finish
off, the question

01:24:58.820 --> 01:25:02.160
here is why does
Einstein give up on this.

01:25:02.160 --> 01:25:06.470
And the answer, I think, is
because in addition to his-- as

01:25:06.470 --> 01:25:09.150
he started at the
beginning of his career,

01:25:09.150 --> 01:25:14.470
he says with the
quantum theory of light

01:25:14.470 --> 01:25:17.520
and with special relativity,
ignore your physical pictures.

01:25:17.520 --> 01:25:21.120
Try and look at the
phenomena and explain those.

01:25:21.120 --> 01:25:25.710
And by 1935, that becomes
very difficult for him.

01:25:25.710 --> 01:25:28.545
Because the phenomenology
becomes too strange.

01:25:28.545 --> 01:25:30.420
One of the things that
quantum mechanics does

01:25:30.420 --> 01:25:38.590
is it takes away the
immediate ability

01:25:38.590 --> 01:25:39.990
to visualize physical systems.

01:25:39.990 --> 01:25:40.490
There.

01:25:40.490 --> 01:25:44.530
English is my first
language sometimes.

01:25:44.530 --> 01:25:49.010
And that's an aesthetic
failure on Einstein's part.

01:25:49.010 --> 01:25:52.360
He had the intellectual
capacity and explicitly said,

01:25:52.360 --> 01:25:55.080
quantum mechanics is a
logically consistent theory

01:25:55.080 --> 01:25:58.280
that incredibly powerfully
describes lots of problems.

01:25:58.280 --> 01:25:59.400
He said that in print.

01:25:59.400 --> 01:26:02.700
He nominated Schrodinger and
Heisenberg for Nobel Prizes

01:26:02.700 --> 01:26:03.400
twice.

01:26:03.400 --> 01:26:04.710
I mean, he wasn't stupid.

01:26:04.710 --> 01:26:05.940
He was Albert Einstein.

01:26:05.940 --> 01:26:10.090
But he was aesthetically
incapable of pursuing

01:26:10.090 --> 01:26:12.800
this new physics
in ways that were

01:26:12.800 --> 01:26:17.874
possible under the research
possibilities of the time.

01:26:17.874 --> 01:26:19.540
And that is what I
would leave you with.

01:26:19.540 --> 01:26:22.632
Physics is an aesthetic as well
as an intellectual pursuit.

01:26:22.632 --> 01:26:23.340
So thank you all.

01:26:23.340 --> 01:26:24.890
[APPLAUSE]

